The patient, a 27-year-old woman at 38 weeks' gestation, underwent a vacuum-assisted delivery due to an arrest in the second stage of labor. Postpartum examination revealed a third-degree laceration in the vagina extending into the perineum at the 6 o'clock position. This type of injury is significant because it involves not only the vaginal mucosa and perineal skin but also the anal sphincter muscles, which are crucial for maintaining fecal continence. 

Given the extent and location of the laceration, the patient is at a high risk for experiencing complications related to the anal sphincter's function. Among the options provided, the most likely complication directly related to a third-degree perineal laceration is fecal incontinence. This is because the damage to the anal sphincter muscles can impair their ability to control the passage of stool effectively, leading to involuntary leakage of feces.

