The patient presents with symptoms of eye dryness and a foreign body sensation in the eyes, along with mucosal ulceration and atrophy in the oral cavity. These symptoms are characteristic of Sjögren's syndrome, an autoimmune disorder that primarily affects the exocrine glands, particularly the salivary and lacrimal glands. The biopsy of the lower lip showing marked lymphocytic infiltration of the minor salivary glands further supports this diagnosis, as it is a hallmark feature of Sjögren's syndrome.

Among the options provided, Anti-Sjögren's syndrome type B (SS-B) antibody is most closely associated with Sjögren's syndrome. SS-B antibodies are one of the specific autoantibodies found in patients with Sjögren's syndrome, although they are not present in all cases. The other options are associated with different autoimmune conditions: anti-centromere antibody with limited systemic scleroderma, anti-Jo-1 antibody with polymyositis and dermatomyositis, anti-Scl-70 antibodies with diffuse systemic scleroderma, and anti-double stranded DNA with systemic lupus erythematosus.

